  url = {https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qe7oM9pJpiI&list=PLCrWEzJgSUqzNzh6mjWsWUu-lSK59VXP6&index=7},
  abstract = {We discuss computational and graphical probabilistic methods for assessing and communicating causal effect heterogeneity. The methods we discuss are especially timely as psychological research is placing increasing emphasis on variation among individuals' effects. Established practices in studying heterogeneity predominantly focus on point estimates and ignore uncertainties, and thereby substitute robust inferences with guesses based on expectations. We provide a walk-through of effective heterogeneity reporting and display tools that appropriately convey measures of uncertainty using Bayesian hierarchical models. We illustrate the concepts and computations behind four heterogeneity metrics based on the posterior distribution of the effects' heterogeneity distribution. These tools are enabled by (1) modern Bayesian methods that return random draws from models' multivariate posterior distributions, and (2) accessible interfaces (brms) to state of the art estimation algorithms (Stan). We discuss the benefits of both and illustrate their uses with example datasets from psychological research.},
